❌Don’t book this hotel with points!! 

I usually talk about great hotels and resorts that you can book with points. But with the new Hyatt category changes I wanted to highlight one you probably shouldn’t book with points. 

This is Hyatt Centric Key West, which just moved to a category 8 which costs 35k to 45k points per night!! 😲😬😑

Don’t get me wrong. It’s a nice hotel in an excellent location if you want to explore Key West on foot. But it’s not a category 8 hotel! You could pay the same number of points to stay at a place like Park Hyatt Paris…and these 2 hotels aren’t in the same ballpark.

I don’t know what Hyatt was thinking with this change but it doesn’t make sense and you will probably be disappointed if you spend all of your Hyatt points here. 

For context, I stayed here when it was a category 6 that cost 25k points per night…and I thought it was a little overpriced then.😬

The good, bad, and ugly of the Park MGM hotel in Las Vegas. 🎰

✅ GOOD: The room was comfortable with plenty of plugs, a couch, and a great shower. Eataly, an Italian marketplace, is located on the casino level.

❌ BAD: There was no coffee maker or fridge in the room. The pools were small and looked pretty meh.

🤮UGLY: The carpet in the hallways was disgusting.

How To Book:

Park MGM is a Hyatt category 4 hotel that can be booked with Hyatt free night certificates or 12k to 18k points per night. If you book through Hyatt you’ll have to pay resort fees (although I had luck getting these fees waived on an award stay). If you have MGM Gold status you can book through MGM and have the resort fees waived.

🏆If you have Hyatt Explorist or Globalist status, you can match to MGM Gold.

The miles and points community focuses a lot on business and first class redemptions. While those are great, many people would rather save their miles to take more flights in economy.

 ➡️ I wanted to test out the middle ground: PREMIUM ECONOMY!

In Premium Economy, you’ll get: 

•A wider seat with more pitch and a greater recline
•A foot rest
•Upgraded pillow/blanket and an amenity kit
•Better meal service
•Upgraded boarding position 
•2 free checked bags

I think Premium Economy is definitely worth it. It’s a great option if you’re short on points or are traveling with a large group (it’s a great option for families with kids).

🚢 ALASKA CRUISE HIGHLIGHTS🚢

Sled Dog Summer Camp | Juneau, Alaska

🚢 5 Travel Tips for an Alaska Cruise

1. Pack layers. It’s possible to experience multiple seasons in a single day in Alaska so bring lots of layers to keep up with the weather.

2. Book a balcony room. You’ll appreciate a private space to enjoy the scenery, especially when the public decks get crowded.

3. Book shore excursions and prepare to pay a lot. To get the most out of your cruise, you’ll want to book tours in port. Whether you book them through the cruise line or independently, know that they won’t be cheap.

4. Manage your expectations. Weather can cause your scenic cruising days to be canceled. Plus, glaciers in Alaska may not be as majestic as you are picturing in your mind.

5. Bring binoculars and a camera with a zoom lens. Don’t assume you’ll be able to see wildlife with your naked eye from the ship.

This is my PSA for the day: Check your credit card accounts to make sure you’re getting the correct number of points. I’ve had 5 Hyatt charges code incorrectly this year on my Hyatt credit card.

All of these were from Hyatt Ziva properties. The first 3 charges had the wrong hotel name so they didn’t code as a Hyatt. 

The last 2 charges were charged before I got to the hotel so they coded as an online travel agency instead of a hotel, so even though my account said “Hyatt Ziva” I only earned 1x points instead of 4x. 

If this happens to you, you need to call Chase to get it fixed. It will most likely be a huge PITA and will take a long time (the first time this happened it took 2 months to get my missing points).

It’s always smart to double check your credit card statements because mistakes can happen.
